This paper deals with topology control algorithms in wireless sensor networks, which are typically studied in the computer networks and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The use of game theory to optimize network lifetime suggests a possible fit with the game theory and economics (cs.GT) sub-category. The fact that the algorithm is distributed and involves cooperation between nodes suggests a possible fit with the distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The use of energy consumption and availability as key factors in the algorithm suggests a possible fit with the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the use of optimization techniques to improve network performance suggests a possible fit with the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
